"id":"mk19_bb_en_s6",
"title":{
"__html":"Pituitary Hormone Deficiency"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"2a93ac",
"children":[
"Pituitary Hormone Deficiency"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s6_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"9d2360",
"children":[
"Panhypopituitarism is a condition in which adequate production of all anterior pituitary hormones is lacking, usually because of a large tumor (see Pituitary Adenomas following), apoplexy, necrosis, autoimmune disorder, or complications of pituitary surgery."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0d6364",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Pituitary apoplexy"
]
},
" results from sudden pituitary hemorrhage or infarction and is often associated with sudden headache, visual change, ophthalmoplegia, and altered mental status."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"8fb0c7",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Postpartum pituitary necrosis (Sheehan syndrome)"
]
},
" is caused by silent pituitary infarction; is usually associated with obstetric hemorrhage and hypotension; and most commonly presents with amenorrhea, a postpartum inability to lactate, and fatigue."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b76460",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Lymphocytic hypophysitis"
]
},
" causes hypopituitarism and, possibly, symptoms of a mass lesion. Most cases of lymphocytic hypophysitis occur during or after pregnancy but may be the result of cancer immunotherapy with checkpoint inhibitors."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f4765d",
"children":[
"The posterior pituitary releases vasopressin and oxytocin directly into the systemic circulation. Deficiencies of these hormones can occur independent of anterior pituitary dysfunction."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"648ead",
"children":[
"Look for symptoms of panhypopituitarism:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"daf2d3",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"fatigue, nausea, vomiting, weight loss, or abdominal pain (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"adrenocorticotropic hormone",
"children":[
"ACTH"
]
},
" deficiency)"
]
},
" "
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f234d5",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"cold intolerance, weight gain, or constipation (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"thyroid-stimulating hormone",
"children":[
"TSH"
]
},
" deficiency)"
]
},
" "
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"ece8fa",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"visual field diagram showing bitemporal loss of vision (mass effect on the optic chiasm)"
]
},
" "
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"22e3b5",
"children":[
"amenorrhea, loss of libido, or erectile dysfunction (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"follicle-stimulating hormone",
"children":[
"FSH"
]
},
"/",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"luteinizing hormone",
"children":[
"LH"
]
},
" deficiency)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b0c9f9",
"children":[
"loss of muscle mass (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"growth hormone",
"children":[
"GH"
]
},
" deficiency)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"68db95",
"children":[
"Look for symptoms of posterior pituitary dysfunction:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"32bfdd",
"children":[
"polydipsia, polyuria, and nocturia (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"diabetes insipidus",
"children":[
"DI"
]
},
" secondary to ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"antidiuretic hormone",
"children":[
"ADH"
]
},
" deficiency)"
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s6_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c5f1e9",
"children":[
"Pituitary hormone deficiency is confirmed by documenting target-organ hormone deficiency and a corresponding low or “normal” serum pituitary hormone level. Stimulation testing may be needed to document hypopituitarism."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_s6_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"8d6867",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"After documenting pituitary hormone deficiency, select dedicated pituitary MRI."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"31d0be",
"children":[
"It is not necessary to measure serum FSH/LH levels in women who have normal menstrual cycles."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s6_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1bc241",
"children":[
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Patients with panhypopituitarism require daily thyroxine and cortisol replacement."
]
},
" Androgen replacement is appropriate for men with hypogonadism, and estrogen replacement is used for premenopausal women with hypogonadism. GH replacement is rarely indicated."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"caf2ab",
"children":[
"Thyroxine dosing for central hypothyroidism is based on serum free ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"free thyroxine",
"children":[
"T",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
}
]
},
" rather than TSH levels."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d846e6",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"T",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" replacement is indicated only after hypoadrenalism has been ruled out or treated."
]
},
" "
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s6_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"7c45d5",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 65-year-old man was diagnosed with ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"small cell lung cancer",
"children":[
"SCLC"
]
},
" 20 years ago and received chemotherapy and chest and cranial irradiation. Physical examination shows hypotension, tachycardia, and small testes. Serum sodium is 123 mEq/L."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"2473ac",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose hypopituitarism. For management, select immediate replacement with stress doses of hydrocortisone followed by confirmatory testing."
]
}
]
}
]
},
